The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal

 Thursday, September 22, 2005 

 BRIEFS

 Asansol, Sept. 21: The CPM will fight the Centres new labour policy, Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee said today.

 We wont allow the UPA government to impose anything which will harm the interest of labour. It is trying to impose a hire-and-fire policy in the labour sector which we will oppose, the chief minster said.

 Calcutta: A seven-member committee constituted by Prime Minister Manmohan Singh is arriving on a three-day visit to the city on Friday to study the socio-economic condition of Muslims in Bengal as part of a nationwide survey. It will prepare a report on the social, economic and educational status of the Muslim community of India.

 Calcutta: An irrigation department engineer drowned when the mechanised boat he was travelling in overturned in the Bidyadhari. Three others went missing.

 Santiniketan: The Chhatra Parishad, which controls the students union at Visva-Bharati, launched an indefinite strike from Wednesday to protest police atrocities. Vice-chancellor Sujit Basu said: We condemn police harassment, if any, but classes should not be affected.

 Krishnagar: Two days after he allegedly teased a girl, Dinesh Das, 22, hanged himself on Tuesday. Police found a suicide note from the traders house near Dhantala, about 70 km from Calcutta, blaming seven persons for his death.

 Burdwan: Maoists have called a 24-hour bandh on Thursday in the Burdwan, Nadia and Murshidabad districts to protest against harassment by police.




